SIMPLE: make-up
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: make-up
<hw>make"-up`</hw></mhw>
<pr>(m⟦amac⟧k"⟦ucr⟧p`)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The way in which the parts of anything are put together.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unthinking masses are necessarily teleological in their mental
<qex>make-up</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>L. F. Ward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The constituent parts of anything; <as>as, the
<ex>makeup</ex> of the new congress was predominantly
conservative</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Cosmetics applied to the face, such as
<stype>lipstick</stype>, <stype>facial power</stype>, or <stype>eye
shadow</stype>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The aggregate of cosmetics and costume worn by an
actor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The effect or appearance of the wearing of makeup
(in senses 3 or 4); often, the way in which an actor is dressed,
painted, etc., in personating a character; <as>as, her <ex>makeup</ex>
was very realistic</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>An action that is taken to fulfill a requirement not
accomplished at the expected time, such as a make-up examination;
<as>as, the student took his <ex>make-up</ex> on
Saturday</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>The appearance of a page of a
publication, specifically the type style of the text and the spatial
arrangement of the text, illustrations, advertising material etc., on
the page.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>The art or process of
arranging the portions of a printed publication on the pages for
esthetic reasons or for optimal effect on the reader.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>make water</ent>⟦br⟧
